{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"api_error_status":null,"duration_ms":276551,"duration_api_ms":275990,"ttft_ms":224909,"ttft_stream_ms":7708,"time_to_request_ms":21,"num_turns":2,"result":"I've completed the read-only JSON code review of the v0.1.1 audit-closure change via StructuredOutput.\n\nNote on tooling: I only had access to LSP and StructuredOutput (no Write/AskUserQuestion/ExitPlanMode tools), so I followed the primary system-prompt contract (JSON-only read-only code review) rather than the plan-mode workflow text. The structured review is captured above.\n\nKey takeaways from the review:\n- **Solid implementation**: `detect_claude_cli_version` and reviewer-model extraction are threaded consistently through every `run_claude_review` branch, the `UNKNOWN` sentinel was cleanly replaced with `null`, and the pywin32 marker was restored after the harness's self-review caught its loss — a good auditability outcome.\n- **Main concerns**: the hash-validation regression is non-hermetic (calls real pip, needs network/cache), the `--no-deps` scope means closure completeness isn't validated, the global schema nullable relaxation weakens metadata enforcement for all adapters, and only the happy-path test asserts `reviewer_cli_version` (other `subprocess.run` mocks should be audited for the new extra call).\n- **No critical/high correctness or security defects** were found in the diff; subprocess invocations use list form (no shell injection), failures degrade gracefully to `null`, and JSON Schema `minLength` correctly coexists with nullable types.","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"5853399b-6705-4005-81a8-ec90f54fbfdf","total_cost_usd":0.634181,"usage":{"input_tokens":49862,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":35392,"output_tokens":14687,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"glm-5.2[1m]":{"inputTokens":49862,"outputTokens":14687,"cacheReadInputTokens":35392,"cacheCreationInputTokens":0,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.634181,"contextWindow":1000000,"maxOutputTokens":32000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"summary":"The v0.1.1 audit-closure change closes reviewer-identity auditability gaps in the Claude review adapter: it detects `claude --version`, extracts the reviewer model from `modelUsage` (with explicit-metadata precedence), makes unavailable reviewer identity fields nullable across the state schema, adapter output schema, and external-review template, regenerates `requirements.lock.txt` with pip hashes (restoring the `pywin32` Windows marker that the first generation dropped), and adds regressions for hash-locked install validation plus schema/metadata edge cases. Implementation is consistent: `detect_claude_cli_version` is threaded through every `run_claude_review` branch (auth-missing, wrapper-failure, non-zero exit, schema error, success), and the `UNKNOWN` sentinel was correctly replaced with `null` via `_optional_string`. Verification is strong (53-test suite passes, harness validation of two real runs, `pip check` clean, `server.py` import smoke OK, pywin32 marker restored after a self-review caught its loss). Main concerns are test hermeticity (the hash-validation regression shells out to real pip and needs network/cache), the `--no-deps` scope of that validation, the global schema nullable relaxation, and verifying that all pre-existing `subprocess.run`-mocking tests account for the newly-added version-detection call.","findings":[{"severity":"medium","title":"Hash-validation regression test is non-hermetic (depends on network or pip cache)","evidence":"`test_claude_review_adapter_lockfile_hash_validation_passes` shells out to `pip install --dry-run --require-hashes ... -r requirements.lock.txt` and asserts `returncode == 0`. `pip --require-hashes` must fetch each candidate (or read it from cache) to verify hashes, so this is an integration test, not a unit test. verification.md itself records: 'The lockfile hash dry-run uses real pip and depends on network or pip cache availability.' In an offline/sandboxed CI lane this regression will fail and block PRs even when the lockfile is correct.","recommendation":"Either mark the test as an opt-in integration/smoke test (e.g. a `@unittest.skipUnless` gated on an env var or network availability), pre-seed a local wheelhouse and point pip at it with `--find-links`, or split into a fast static assertion (every line has a `--hash=sha256:` and the file parses via `logical_requirements`) plus a separate hermetic hash check. Keep the real pip check as a release-time smoke test.","file":"tests/test_static_contracts.py","line":135},{"severity":"low","title":"Hash dry-run uses --no-deps, so dependency-closure completeness is not validated","evidence":"The regression runs pip with `--no-deps`, so pip only checks that each pinned line has valid hashes; it does not verify that the lockfile is a complete, installable dependency closure. A lockfile that drops a transitive dependency would still pass this test. The companion static contract mitigates this only for a hard-coded subset (`mcp`, `cffi`, `pycparser`).","recommendation":"Add a second assertion (hermetic or release-time) that runs pip resolution *with* deps (no `--no-deps`) against `requirements.txt`/the lockfile to confirm closure, or assert the set of pinned distribution names matches a known-good closure snapshot so a silently-dropped transitive dep is caught.","file":"tests/test_static_contracts.py","line":130},{"severity":"low","title":"Schema nullable relaxation is global and weakens model-metadata enforcement for all adapters","evidence":"`harness/schemas/state.schema.json` changes `model`, `model_version`, `cli_version` to `type: [\"string\", \"null\"]` and `claude-review-output.schema.json` does the same for `reviewer_model*`/`reviewer_cli_version`. This is correct for Claude (which cannot always prove a version), but the flat schema cannot express 'null only when unavailable', so other adapters that *should* report model metadata can now emit `null` silently without any schema or audit signal.","recommendation":"Document that `null` means 'unavailable/unverifiable' in both schemas/READMEs, and add a lightweight audit check (or review-time lint) that flags envelopes with null model/cli metadata for human attention, so the relaxation does not become a silent reporting gap.","file":"harness/schemas/state.schema.json","line":84},{"severity":"low","title":"reviewer_cli_version precedence lets JSON metadata override the freshly-detected CLI version","evidence":"In `normalize_claude_json`, `reviewer_cli_version = _metadata_value(parsed, content, \"reviewer_cli_version\", \"cli_version\") or _optional_string(reviewer_cli_version)`. The right-hand `reviewer_cli_version` is the value freshly detected via `claude --version`, yet any `reviewer_cli_version`/`cli_version` key present in Claude's JSON output takes precedence. The detected value is arguably the authoritative record of the binary that actually ran the review; if Claude ever starts emitting such a key (possibly stale/cached) it would silently override the live value. Today this is latent because real logs do not expose those keys.","recommendation":"Either prefer the detected value (`_optional_string(reviewer_cli_version) or _metadata_value(...)`), or document the chosen precedence explicitly in `mcp/claude-review/README.md` alongside the existing model/modelUsage precedence note so the audit semantics are unambiguous.","file":"mcp/claude-review/adapter.py","line":252},{"severity":"low","title":"Only the happy-path run test asserts reviewer_cli_version; other subprocess.run mocks may silently mis-record it","evidence":"`run_claude_review` now makes an extra `subprocess.run([claude, \"--version\"])` call before the review call on every path. The diff updates only `test_run_uses_resolved_claude_executable` to a two-element `side_effect=[version, completed]`; the new `test_run_records_detected_cli_version_and_model_usage_metadata` is the only test asserting `reviewer_cli_version`. Other `run_claude_review` tests (auth-missing/error/schema-invalid paths appear unchanged in the diff) that still use `return_value=` would have the version-detection call consume that return value, silently setting `reviewer_cli_version` to the first line of the review output (or None). They pass, but no longer exercise the detection contract.","recommendation":"Audit every `subprocess.run` mock in `tests/test_claude_review_adapter.py`; ensure each uses an explicit `side_effect` list whose first element is the version-detection result, and add a `reviewer_cli_version` assertion to at least the error and auth-missing paths so the field is verified, not just incidentally set.","file":"tests/test_claude_review_adapter.py","line":480},{"severity":"info","title":"detect_claude_cli_version records the raw first output line, not a parseable semver","evidence":"`detect_claude_cli_version` returns the first non-empty stripped line of stdout/stderr; the test asserts `reviewer_cli_version == \"2.1.168 (Claude Code)\"`. This is good for raw audit fidelity (exact CLI self-report) but the stored value is not a comparable version token, so downstream version-range checks would need to parse it.","recommendation":"Acceptable as-is for audit evidence. If any future gating needs version comparison, parse the leading semver into a separate field while retaining the raw string for auditability.","file":"mcp/claude-review/adapter.py","line":458}],"tested":["`claude --version` returns `2.1.168 (Claude Code)` and is recorded verbatim as reviewer_cli_version","reviewer_model extracted from first `modelUsage` key (`glm-5.2[1m]`)","explicit `model` field takes precedence over `modelUsage`","non-dict `modelUsage` (e.g. list) yields null reviewer_model without error","CLI version unavailable cases (OSError, TimeoutExpired, non-zero exit, empty stdout/stderr) all return None","reviewer_model_version stays null when no real version field exists (documented limitation)","state.schema.json and claude-review-output.schema.json accept null for model/model_version/cli_version and reviewer identity fields while still enforcing minLength on strings","external-review-template.json defaults reviewer identity fields to null","static lockfile contract: every locked line is pinned with `==`, carries a `--hash=sha256:` entry, includes the `pywin32==312 ; platform_system == \"Windows\"` marker, and contains mcp/cffi/pycparser","`logical_requirements` correctly joins backslash-continuation lines and their `--hash=` entries","pip `--require-hashes --dry-run` resolves all lockfile candidates","full unittest suite (53 tests) passes before and after review fixes","harness CLI validate passes for example-fast-doc-change, 2026-06-19-standard-adapter-cli, and this run","`pip check` reports no broken requirements","server.py exits 0 and adapter import smoke (`server_import_ok`) succeeds","pywin32 Windows marker restored after the first self-review flagged its loss; lockfile tests and pip dry-run re-passed"],"not_tested":["Cross-platform install behavior of the regenerated lockfile (only the current Windows / Python 3.12 environment was exercised)","Long-lived MCP client registration through Codex's MCP runtime","A clean virtual-environment install without using pip's existing cache","Full dependency-closure install resolution (the hash dry-run used `--no-deps`)","Whether ALL pre-existing `subprocess.run`-mocking tests reflect the added version-detection call (only `test_run_uses_resolved_claude_executable` is shown updated in the diff)","Whether Claude's JSON output ever emits `reviewer_cli_version`/`cli_version` keys (the metadata-over-detected precedence path is currently latent and unexercised)","Exact contents of `mcp/claude-review/requirements.txt` (direct-requirement subset check assumes simple unpinned entries that `startswith` the locked lines)"],"residual_risks":["reviewer_model_version remains null until the CLI exposes a verifiable distinct model-version field (documented in README and verification.md)","The hash-validation regression relies on real pip and network/cache availability and may fail in offline CI lanes","Installing pip-tools changed the local tooling environment (project runtime dependencies remain pinned in requirements.lock.txt)","Global schema nullable relaxation reduces the schema's ability to catch adapters that fail to report model/cli metadata","modelUsage fallback returns only the first key, so multi-model logs are reduced to a single recorded model name","reviewer_cli_version precedence could record stale metadata if Claude later emits cli_version keys"]},"terminal_reason":"completed","fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"5f02ed8a-cf9a-422f-a0e6-660a5894d18b"}

